ranslation into English) of French   Terrien   ‘owner of a farmland’ or of its altered form   Therrien  . Compare   Pharmer  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Fermore was born about 1375, in England, his father, Henry Fermore, was 27 and his mother, Agnes Whitney Fermor Langford, was 35. He married Lady Agnes Fermour in 1394. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1415, at the age of 42."},"et":{"abt 1375–Abt 1415":"umbes 1375–umbes 1415","1375–1415":"1375–1415","1377–Female":"1377–Surnud","1395–1465":"1395–1465","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1340–1465":"1340–1465","1415":"1415","1465":"1465","1377":"1377","Abt 1375":"umbes 1395","1375":"1375","1340":"1340","1395":"1395","1394":"1394","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","abt 1375":"umbes 1375","Abt 1415":"umbes 1415","Witney, Oxfordshire, England":"Witney, Oxfordshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"abt 1375–Abt 1415":"noin 1375–noin 1415","1375–1415":"1375–1415","1377–Female":"1377–Kuollut","1395–1465":"1395–1465",